Parliament does not support the amendment granting freedom to Timoshenko
Today, the Parliament of Ukraine, in its amendment to the Code of Criminal Procedure, rejected the attempt to repeal the article condemning the opposition leader, Julia Timoshenko.
The amendment, which would lead to the release of the former Prime Minister in prison, was rejected during the second reading of the draft law on the mitigation of sentences for economic offences.
In October, Timoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison for signing a gas deal with Russia, which was found to be inconvenient.
The sentence is not yet final; the court will consider the appeal of Timoshenko in December.
Timoshenko claims that the sentence is the political seat of the regime; in the West, the process is also suspected of bias.
The proposal to repeal Article 365 of the Code of Criminal Procedure, under which the former Prime Minister was convicted, was supported by 147 members of Parliament.
It would require 226 votes to ratify it.
