V Need for Speed: Escape takes place in America.
Overview
What was supposed to be a carefree walk turned into a routine morning trip to work because of a series of completely inappropriate and careless mistakes.
Ambition was to some extent satisfied, but that is not important, since no one clearly wanted to do too much work.
Before leaving the new version with the title "Fleece" they had high hopes.
It was expected to move the previous Need For Speed series in a new direction; demonstration versions indicated that the game would take a decent place in the genre of racing games.
We were curious to see parts of the game where the main hero gets out of the car and runs.
As often happens with the NFS, in the end much is different from what we expected.
The game is a pretty good arcade race, but the general impression is a few unnecessary mistakes that have been present in this series of games for several years.
So it's not really a mistake, it's an inexplicable web of developers.
The adventure begins very well.
You're becoming part of a story whose main hero, Jack, decides to solve some personal problems by participating in an illegal race across America.
You get in a car on the west coast, in San Francisco, and your job is to get to New York first.
There are some interesting features to this idea.
The route consists of ten stages divided into more than fifty races.
This means that each race runs on its own route, and individual stages take place in a diverse and interesting environment.
So there is no feeling that the same thing is happening all the time.
Although the schedule is at the same level as in previous parts of the series, it is nice to look at some routes.
Still, the game does not give rise to strong emotions.
Although driving through the desert, in the autumn suburbs, or in the snowy mountains, it is a pleasure.
In addition, the race is sometimes revived by an unusual detail.
In the desert, for example, you find yourself in a sandstorm that greatly reduces visibility.
On the other hand, the mountains need to be careful not to get under the avalanche.
Individual races are pretty well organized.
There are only a few varieties, but that's enough.
For a while you try to outrun a few rivals (in fact, the usual race); then you try to improve time (the standard race with the meter); or you compete with one opponent.
Among other things, you encounter police from time to time, which makes your task even more difficult.
The components outside the car are new.
It's just an interactive animation where most of the time Jack's running away from someone and you have to help him by pressing the buttons he needs at the right time.
It's not that hard.
Although it is surprising that these fragments are much smaller than you might expect (three to be exact).
In fact, it turns out that it's good for the game, because it doesn't suit you; given the above, it's one of the things that makes the game more interesting.
The racing model follows previous models.
That means she's no longer something special, but that can't be considered a disadvantage.
If you're looking for an imitation of real life, you'll have to look elsewhere.
Still, this model of driving is very suitable for dynamic racing, although better options can be found in the market.
So far, so good.
But after a while, problems begin.
Unlike the driver's model, the collision model isn't so good.
You don't expect complex changes and collisions from a game like this, but if you have no idea how your car will behave, something will happen.
Usually, if you drive or drive past a car in a traffic jam, you sometimes touch another car a little bit, and yet sometimes in a similar situation your car starts to spin.
Or it would crash.
It's not that important because of the restart system, but that's enough to ruin the fun.
The restarts are arranged so that if you crash or get away from the route, the game will bring you back to the point where it broke.
However, only five restarts are available for each race.
If you use them all, you'll have to start the race from the beginning.
It's useful if something doesn't work out, but you can't rely entirely on it.
Sometimes restarts are not enough, and you have to learn a certain part of the race.
An important flaw in the game is the fact that the same things often happen in the same places.
For example, some turns have to be done in a certain way, or you just don't fit in.
In other cases, you meet civilian cars at a certain location in the same configuration regardless of whether you arrive first, fifth, five seconds earlier or a minute later.
This is particularly annoying in situations where you see your opponent passing easily between two vehicles moving in the opposite direction, while when you are going there, the cars are already in such a position that you need to either drive around or drop speed.
It doesn't matter when you're around them; it's all arranged that the situation always happens right in front of your nose.
There are other advantages to rivals.
During the game, you find several places where, regardless of time, the same rival is chasing you in the same place.
It's especially obvious at the end of the game, on the long bridge where you're going in the opposite direction.
Apparently, your opponent must stand before you no matter what.
The fact is, when he's ahead of you, he's making your review worse, which leads to one or more accidents on this site.
You can understand the attempt to make the game more interesting and full of adrenaline, but it is so obvious that it is rapidly starting to cause irritation.
It's a shame, because despite the simple model of driving, the game is interesting and sometimes so full of events that you don't have time to pay attention to what's going on around you.
It doesn't matter what you don't miss -- a concept with fifty unique routes, a sequence of races or something.
The idea of changing cars during the race is unusual.
You need to keep track of the fillings on the way, because it's on them that your car can change, even though in most cases what you already have is enough.
The cars are divided into three categories.
Sports cars are suitable for cities; powerful American cars for direct cuts of the road; and exotic supersports for technical driving, for example, on curved mountain routes.
The main story mode is closely related to the mode challenge; these are the races on individual sites that you will learn from the course of the game.
Here you win for your personal business both medals and points common to the regimes of challengers and story.
Many opportunities are available for higher driving levels, starting with cars and completing profile data.
In addition, the profile is linked to the Autolog online function, which, among other things, compares the results you have achieved with the results of other players and provides communication to the public.
Here is another flaw that is difficult to understand; this is an example from the last race in sequence.
You and your car get into a subway tunnel (we'll assume so), where you're running on the tracks in the dark (we'll assume so).
Your speedometer shows the numbers from 150 to 200 km/h (we'll assume so), when you suddenly get hit by a subway train, turning your car into a scrap metal.
For a few days, our editors discussed whether, at the time of the game, no one really thought for a second, or whether its creators really thought we were such morons.
The technical component of the game is nothing special; but the overall impression from the video series is mostly pleasant, sometimes even shocking.
Although it is unfortunate that, at some critical times, the quality of the recording sometimes decreases quite strongly.
This is particularly true of events involving a large number of participants, where a good record would not be particularly helpful to you either.
Sound's fine; soundtrack's a fan.
To please the widest possible youth audience, the soundtrack 'entered compositions of different styles'; but few people would buy the game because of its music.
General impression of Need for Speed: It ran pretty messy.
If the game avoided clearly unnecessary mistakes, we could honestly say that the escape is the best part of the NFS over the last few years.
In any case, the game leaves a sense of inadequacy.
Of course, it's a good time, but get ready for the flaws to blind you like an airport searchlight.
