Travel price dynamics since 1989
Until 1989, only five public tourist agencies could work in the former Czechoslovakia: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
Since travel to the West was severely restricted, tourist agencies at the time were mainly selling tours to the Socialist bloc countries.
Thus, Czech tourists took vacations to the German Democratic Republic; the Soviet Union (Sochi, Crimea on the Black Sea); Bulgaria; Romania (both countries on the Black Sea); and Hungary (Balaton).
The only exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when we had the opportunity to travel to Yugoslavia, and the Yugoslav regime then returned to the West, which imposed significant restrictions on the travel of Czech tourists to Yugoslavia.
A major paradox of the socialist period was that citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. and Czechoslovakia) were not allowed individual visits to socialist countries.
If a Czechoslovak citizen wanted to go on his own, for example, to the Soviet Union or Poland, a letter of invitation was needed from that country; otherwise it was not possible to travel individually.
At the time, travel agencies offered trips to the West, but it was either to stand in line all night, with a sleeping bag, or to have good friends in the agency.
And that wasn't all.
The currency permit was necessary for travel to the West, and was not issued to politically unreliable people who were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czechoslovakian currency was not freely convertible; it was not possible to obtain money (Western currency) for travel to the West without a currency permit.
The Czechs often spent their vacations at home, leading to a large number of cottages and summer homes, which is still a practice.
Since 1989, tourism in the Czech Republic has thus survived the real revolution.
While prior to 1989 vacations in the GDR or Bulgaria were the culmination of our travels, last year the Czechs held 4.5 million vacations in countries around the world.
The great paradox that we no longer realize is that before 1989 we were unable to visit Croatia freely, the most popular one, since it was part of the former Yugoslavia.
In early 1990, the need for a visa to the neighbouring countries of Western Europe had been lifted, with the beginning of a huge wave of short trips mainly to Vienna and Germany.
The Czechoslovakians couldn't get enough travel to the West.
For example, in Paris, Czech tourists slept in parks in tents because their income was not enough at the hotel or boarding house at the time.
A typical feature of Czech tourism at that time was the desire to bring its own food (conservations, halls, etc.) to save money.
Another important moment is the introduction of a freely converted Czech crown, and decades later our tourists can finally buy the Western currency freely.
Our standard of living and average income increased, which led to another important circumstance around 1997.
Since 1997, increased demand has allowed tourist agencies to prepare regular flights carried out by charter airlines, and compared to the previous one, flights have now become incredibly cheap owing to the possibility of ordering wholesale discounts.
By the end of the 1990s, we didn't need a visa to visit virtually all the developed world countries except the United States, which made our travels even easier.
The next significant event in the history of the post-revolution journeys occurred in 2000 and a great demand led historically to the first direct charter flight from the Czech Republic to the exotic country, Thailand.
Since then, direct charter flights have taken Czech tourists to warm exotic countries, and this winter flights from the Czech Republic will take 12 exotic routes.
About 100,000 Czechs now visit exotic countries every year!
And yet another important development of this period, symbolizing our development after the revolution, took place in 2008.
On 17 November 2008, the United States abolished the need to obtain a visa for Czech tourists, and our country has thus forever joined the most developed world countries.
For the first time in 2008, Czechs spent more than half of their vacations abroad (50.3%); and for the first time in history, they spent more than 15,000 crowns per person while abroad, including their expenses at the destination.
