The Court will approve the digital television transition in Mexico in 2015
Replacing analogue signals to digital signals is one of the most important changes the world has seen in recent years.
The Supreme Court (CC) rejected the constitutional claims made by the Senate and the House of Representatives against the Presidential Decree, which transposes the so-called “transition to digital television” from 2021 to 2015, as eight votes were not collected for its annulment.
A minority of four ministers, including the President of the Court, Juan Silva Mesa, felt that President Felipe Calderon had not exceeded his authority by issuing a decree detailing actions to move to digital terrestrial television.
As a result, the constitutional claims made by the Senate were rejected due to the lack of a qualified majority of eight votes necessary for the court to speak on the constitutionality or unconstitutionality of the decree and remain in force.
The draft statement prepared by Minister Olga Sanchez Cordero proposed declaring the decree unconstitutional, because the regulation of the radio and television programme was a law established by the Federal Telecommunications Commission (Coffetel), in violation of the principles of hierarchical subordination and the legislative reserve.
Only Salvidar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Marguerite Luna and Sanchez Cordero voted in favour of the project.
Under this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies held two constitutional debates to refute the decree and to support the complaints, Minister Sanchez Cordero suspended the application of the decree and all the actions referred to in it regarding the transition to digital broadcasting.
At the ministerial meeting, it was also decided to reject the requirement of the Chamber of Deputies, without entering into a discussion of the draft, also under the responsibility of Minister Sanchez Cordero.
In his speech, the Prime Minister said that he disagreed with the project ' s arguments that the federal executive could not determine the general rules of the measures to be prepared by the State administration.
“I also do not believe that if this had happened, this would have an impact on the autonomy of the regulatory body”, and recalled that public policy planning in strategic areas, such as the telecommunications sector, was relevant to the federal executive, which had a constitutional mandate, State administration.
Replacing analogue signals to digital signals - one of the most important changes in recent years - has resulted in better use of radio-electric spectrum, better signal quality and more channels.
Postponing the transition, he said, would mean delaying the benefits of turning into a digital form that includes meeting public needs, which not only has a technical dimension, “as it covers economic, social, political and national security issues”.
These issues, he said, “require the work of the entire system of State economic governance, which includes a group of authorities which the Constitution unites into the State executive power”.
He recalled that a large number of countries around the world had already completed the transition to digital broadcasting, and had done so with the assistance of the executive, despite the existence of narrow technical institutions.
It cannot be concluded from this that the Government, by adopting the decree under discussion, which in any event affects the competence of the Congress, ensures compliance with the laws adopted by the Legislative Assembly in the administrative sphere, he said.
In Michoakana, they're analyzing the possibility of counting "vote after voice"
According to the data provided in the ERP, the difference between the first and second seats in the Governorial Elections is only 27 per cent, even without counting the 879 votes in the 6,074 Protocols.
The possibility of counting the “vote by vote” is real in the election process in Michoakana this year, where, according to the preliminary results of the election programme (APR), the difference between the first and second seats in the governorial elections is only 27 per cent, even without counting the 879 votes in the 6.074 minutes.
In light of this, the President of the General Council of the Institute of Elections, Michoakana (IVM), Maria de Los Angeles Lánderal Saragosa, recalled that a few days ago, on 9 November, the constituency approved a package of principles to harmonize local rules with federal electoral reform.
It is recalled that Michoakan did not adopt the Constitution or the Electoral Code of the State or the Electoral Law Act, since the State Congress approved reforms shortly before the legal date of entry into force of the electoral process and that the Governor of Leonel Goda Rangel did not include its publication within the time limits set out in the law in the Official Gazette of the State, stating that he had some objections.
On the same day, 9 November, the Supreme Court of Justice (CJ) ruled on the constitutional claim put forward by the local legislative assembly and called the “ineffective and illegal” vote of the State representative on constitutional reform because he has no right to “authorize or support them”.
In an interview on the possibility of “vote after vote”, Maria de Los Angeles Länderal argued that with the adoption of appropriate principles, it would be possible for the General Council of IVM to submit a partial or full vote count to the local electoral authority.
For example, partial recalculation of one or more electoral urns may be made on condition that: the results of the protocols do not coincide; there is no vote and counting of the documents in the urn or is not in the chair ' s possession; or when there are obvious errors or corrections in the protocol.
In addition, the total recalculation in all the ballots in the elections may take place when there is evidence that the difference between the alleged candidate winner of the elections under consideration and those who won the second ballot is less than or equal to one percentage, provided that at the beginning of the session there is a request from the representative of the party and/or coalition that put forward the second of the candidates.
The total recalculation will also be made if, at the end of the normal calculation, it is established that the difference between the winner and the candidate in the second place is less than or equal to one per cent, provided that there is a request from the political party whose candidate has taken second place in the event that the electoral urns that have been taken into account on the partial recalculation are deleted.
It is worth noting that in such a situation there are elections in Morelia, where, according to ERW, the difference between the first and the second places is only 0.16 per cent, not including 129 votes in the total number of 923 minutes.
