UNAM asphalt can avoid cracks
Rafael Herrera, a UNAM chemical researcher, developed a polymer-modified bitumen to produce a mixture of the best quality that is resistant to environmental and temperature effects.
If road coverage signals were to be given attention, there would be a need to repair some 200,000 pits for each rainy season in the capital area in Mexico Valley, says Rafael Herrera Naher, a UNAM chemical researcher, and adds that if the construction and maintenance of asphalted road surfaces were correct, the number of holes could be reduced or reduced to zero.
In his lecture, the Technology View of Pits, read in the International Year of Chemistry, reports that the laboratory for which he is responsible is developing a polymer-modified bitumen to produce a mixture with characteristics close to bitumen, but with better resistance at both high and low temperatures.
Herrera Naher said that this type of modified bitumen could be used in places where the weather was extremely hot, as in some cities in the north, to improve the quality of roads and therefore to counter the education of pits.
He explained that bitumen, the hardest part of oil, is a sequence of hydrocarbons molecules, some high molecular mass, called asphalt, and others low molecular mass called mortars, which together give road cover its characteristic binding behavior.
The related behavior of bitumen is the fact that at high temperatures it behaves as a liquid, at 120 its viscosity is very high, and at 50 degrees Celsius it retains almost a solid state, while at very low temperatures the bitumen becomes fragile, he said.
This means that street asphalt resistance is not constant but changes during the day, depending on natural conditions and temperature, said a chemical engineering specialist.
The hymphaca scientist observed that the streets of Mexico City were largely covered with a flexible coating consisting of six layers of material, three of which included bitumen.
Among the top layers is a bitumen composed of small stones, dropped into bitumen and then pressed.
Every stone that's made up of this coating, he said, is stuffed in bitumen.
When driving and exerting effort, this helps the forces to be very well distributed by road.
If it were modified asphalt, they'd be even better distributed, said the chemical engineer.
On the asphalt coating, he added, placed the last layer, which is called a layer of wear, made of a small stone, which is actually sand, which is also sunk into the asphalt.
Since it will be a layer that will contact the wheels of transport, it must have more resistance than asphalt coating and road friction.
As part of the road surface that will receive and distribute these efforts, the wear layer also requires adequate thickness, and the material from which it is made must be taken into account.
The weather, especially the humidity and temperature changes, are also very important factors for consideration, especially water, he said, because it has a significant impact on asphalt.
When the soil is raw, the water penetrates and it is difficult to get out of there, it causes all layers of the coating to be softened and therefore the formation of the pits.
During the formation of the pits, he said that the first layer of wear was applied and only then did it affect the bitumen, but the damage did not occur immediately, which should be addressed at the first signs of ongoing repair programmes.
A member of the National Research System also explained that the transport load was another important factor in the education of holes, and therefore the thickness of each coating layer must always be linked to the transport load and must be guaranteed to meet this requirement in order to prevent the frequent occurrence of holes.
Rafael Herrera said that there was still much to be done about bitumen, for example, by bituminous emulsions that were already on the market in other countries and even help to make pits with ease and without high temperatures.
